  "prompt": "What's cons and pros for EBS-based AMIs vs. instance-store based AMIs?",
  "response": "Let's break down the pros and cons of EBS-based AMIs vs. Instance-store based AMIs:\n\nEBS-Based AMIs:\n\nPros:\n1. Persistent storage - data survives instance termination\n2. Can be easily stopped and started\n3. Support more complex configurations\n4. Can be modified after creation (snapshot/backup)\n5. Better for long-running instances\n6. Support encryption\n7. Can be resized dynamically\n8. Faster launch times compared to instance store\n\nCons:\n1. Slightly higher cost\n2. Potential performance overhead\n3. Limited by EBS volume performance\n4. Dependent on EBS availability\n\nInstance-Store Based AMIs:\n\nPros:\n1. Higher I/O performance\n2. Lower latency\n3. No additional storage cost\n4. Good for temporary, high-performance computing\n5. Direct access to physical disk\n6. Lower cost for temporary workloads\n\nCons:\n1. Data is lost on instance stop/termination\n2. Cannot be stopped, only terminated\n3. Limited storage capacity\n4. Less flexible\n5. No built-in backup mechanism\n6. Slower instance launch times\n7. No encryption at rest\n8. Limited to specific instance types\n\nRecommendation: Generally, use EBS-based AMIs unless you have specific high-performance, temporary workload requirements.",
